{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_golf_ver02/data/sn83045433/100493287/1907101301/0445.xml":{"full_text":"ELOPERS IN LONDON\nHelen Maloney and Clarkson\nSailed from Quebec.\nSEE LAWYER BEFORE WEDDING\nGroom Questioned Attorney About\n\u201ca Wedding in Fun,\u201d Supposed to\nHave Been that of Bride to the\nMan Named Osborne\u2014Legal Light\nNever Divulged His Conference.\nMontreal, Oct. 12,\u2014Martin Maloney,\nthe Standard Oil magnate, whose\ndaughter was married here on October\n3, arrived to-day to get the story af\nhis daughter's wedding from Bonin, the\nlawyer, who managed the matter.\nIt was also his intention to learn\nwhere his daughter is. The latter part\nof his mission was made easy by the\nreceipt of a cablegram from London,\nannouncing the arrival of the couple,\nwho crossed in the C. P. R. Empress\nof Britain as Mr. and Mrs. Cunning\nham.\nBeyond saying that he will welcome\nthem home and that he does not be\nHeve the story that she was married\ntwo years ago to a man named Os\nborne, Mr. Maloney declined to discuss\nthe matter.\nWhere the couple went after leav\ning the ship cannot be learned. It is\nbelieved, however, they went to Lon\ndon, and intend touring the continent.\nFellow passengers on the Empress of\nBritain said Mr. and Mrs. Cunningham\nwere regarded as a newly wed pair,\nand the descriptions they gave out of\nthe two tailied with those sent out\nof Miss Maloney and Clarkson.\nThe purs\u00e9r said, just before the ves\nsel was about to sail from Quebec, a\ncarriage drew up on the pier and a\nyoung man and woman hastened up\nthe gang plank. The young man\nasked whether he and his wife could\nreceive accommodations, and was told\nthey could. He explained he was Mr.\nCunningham and had just been mar\nried. He and his bride, to avoid their\nfriends, the young man said, decided\nnot to book passage in advance, but\ntrusted to luck that there would be\nvacant state rooms.\n\n\n\n\nMr. and Mrs. Clarence B. Ritchie,\nbrother-in-law and sister of the miss\ning girl, arrived in London yesterday\nand began a search for her. Mr.\nRitchie has a list of the known friends\nof Clarkson in London and Paris, as\nwell as his addresses in both cities\n\n\nand it is through these they hope to\nlocate the elopers.\npa TT HE ry rH.\n\nNew York, Oct. 12.\u2014Clarkson consulted\nPercival G. Barnard, an attorney of 42\nBroadway. Mr. Barnard saw Clarkson\nalone and had not up to to-day teld any\none cf the visit.\n\n\nImmediately after the disappearance of\nClarkson and Miss Maloney, however, the\nfact that Clarkson had visited an attor\nney became public.\nThe only way that Osborne could have\nknown of the fact was through a com\nmunication from either MissiMaloney or\nClarkson. Friends of the two believe\nthat either just before or just after the\ndisappearance of the pair, one of them\nwrote to Osborne telling him of the facts\nand asking him not to put any obstacles\nin the way of an annulment of the \u201cmar\nriage in fun\u201d at Mamaroneck.\n\nj\n\nClarkson went to see Mr. Barnard on\nFriday, September 2I, the day before he\nand Miss Maioney disappeared from\nSpring Lake.\n\n\u201cHe came to my office on Friday,\u201d\nsald Mr. Barnard this morning. \u201cWhen\nhe first came in I thought that he might\nhave been sent to me by the Legal Aid\nBoclety, with which I was formerly con\npected. He said, however, that he had\nnot but did not tell me who it was that\nhad referred him to me. He immediately\nbegan to ask me about a question of mat\nrimony.\n\nPut Hypothetical Question,\n\u201cHe put a hypothetical question to me,\nHe sald that a man and a girl had been\nout in an automobile, and the automobile\nhad broken down. Then he sald they\nboth get married, taking it as a joke.\nThen he hesitated, and said that at least\nthe girl took it as a joke; perhaps. the\nman had not.\n\u201cWe looked up the law together, and I\ntold him that the marriage was valid, but\nI thought that it could be annull\u00aed. When\nhe left I went to the law library and\nfound that the case was as I had stated\nit. All the decisions were one way, and\nin one case that was analagous to the\none he cited the marriage was held to be\nbifiding, but subject to annulment. I\nfound that McClurg vs. Terry, Zl N. J.\nEquity, 225, was practically anaiagous and\nheld as I had stated. He called up later\nto add some details to the story, but I\nwas not in.\n\n\u201cI did not hear anything more about\nmy client until I read of the elopement\nwith Miss Maloney. He told me that the\nmarriage which he questioned me abdut\nhad taken place in a small town near\nNew York.\nCannot Explain Story.\n\u201cClarkson was dressed very neatly in a\nbrown suit, with a soft outing shirt and\na soft pin collar. He did not have on a\n\u201cClarkson was dressed very neatly in a\nbrown suit, with a soft outing shirt and\na soft pin collar, He did not have on a\ngreen derby, and nothing in his costume\nwas especially noticeable.\n\u201c1 cannot imagine how Osborne came\nto know that Clarkson had ever consulted\nme. None but he and I knew of hig visit\nto me. He came Friday afternoon and I\nreceived him absolutely alone. After he\nhad gone 1 said nothing about his visit to\nany one. Even when I found that he had\nafterward disappeared from Spring Lake\nI told no one.\n\u201cThe first time that I found out that\nany one knew of his visit was when I\nread in 2 newspaper that Osborne had\nsaid that Clarkson had consulted a law\nyer before he went away. Yesterday a\nyoung man called at my office who seem\ned to know all the circumstances of\nClarkson's visit to me.\u201d\nA certain curate wag of a painfully\nnervous temperament, and, in conse\nquence, was constantly making awkward\nremarks\u2014intended as compliments\u2014to the\nbishop and others.\"\nHaving distinguished himself in an un\nusual degree during a gathering of clergy\nto an afternoon tea in the bishop's pal\nace, he wag taken to task for his failings\nby a senior curate, who was one of his\ncompanions on the way home,\n\u201cLook here, Bruce,\u201d sald the senior, de\ncidedly, \u201cyou are donkey. Why can't\nyou keep quiet, instead of making your\nasinine remarks? I \u2018am speaking to you\nnow as a brother.\u201d\nLoud laughter interrupted him at this\npoint, and for the moment he did not see\nthe iocke\nMethodists and Negro Bishops\n\nSeventy-two lay delegates td the North\nNebraska Methodist Conference in Omahs\nfailed to authorize a revision in the con\nstitution of the church that would pro\nvide for the election of colored bishops.\nThe vote on the colo bishop proposi\ntion stood 36 to 36, and the result of\nmuch debats.\nwas\nClarkson Saw Lawver.\nBrothers in Asininits\nLOOK WHO'S/,\n\u00a37\n8.\noe\nvi\n\nLD,\n\\z\noa\nMENS LY,\nMNES\nve\nRRS Anam\n4% OVA\nWN,\na a\nZr A PANAS\nTE 1\na\nTo\nARBAB\nCW AW\nXXX EX AX\nXXX XTX\nAWM,\nXA\nCXS\nWAR R\u2122\nA\nA\n\u201cor, ul\nLL eg ed\n\"ONE R\nA)\nWE\nJ\nLAY. ON A\n\na\nASA\nNEW GREEK MINISTER\nLamdros Coromilas to Come\nto Washington.\nIS A POLITICIAN AND AUTHOR\nThird Regularly Accredited Minis\nter from Greece to This Country,\nProbable Greek Bishop May Come\nHere to Exercise Jurisdiction Over\nOrthodox Churches in America,\nLamdrog Ceoromilas, the Greek consul\ngeneral at Saloniki, Turkey, who ac\ncording to an Athens cable, has been\nappointed minister of his government to\nthe United States, belongs to a family\nof authors and writers, and is himself\none of the foremost newspaper men in\nGreece.\nRCRA a che nis\n\nBefore his appointment to the Saloniki\npost, M. Coromilas published the Coro\nmilas Journal in the Greek capital, and\nhis influence on Hellenic politics and\ndiplomacy was recognized throughout his\ncountry. At his Saloniki post, it is un\nderstood, he antagonized British inter\nests, and upon his government's atten\n\u2018tion being called to that fact, he was\nrecalled and offered the Washington post.\n\nM. Coromilas is nearly fifty years old,\nand will make a picturesque addition\nto the diplomatic ccerps of this city.\n~The last Greek minister here was Jean\nGennadius, who arrived here March 1,\n1888. He stayed a very short time and\nthen went to London, to which capital\nhe was also accredited.\nThe diplomatic relations betwesr Amer\nica and Greece have been rather anoma\nlous for many years past. Although the\n\u2018Greek government has not maintained a\nGreek legation in Washington, the United\nStates has always been represented at\n\"Athens by a minister, the incumbent\nbeing John B. Jackson, who also is\ndiplomatic agent for Bulgaria.\nGreece has only had two regularly\naccredited ministers to Washington, so\nfar as the records show. The first was\nAlexandre Rizo Rangabe, who came here\nas envoy extraordinary June 12, 1867. He\nremained here about two years, and,\n\nIramanuel Baptist Church, known to residents of the District about, if not to\nothers, by the name of \u201cPercy Foster's Church,\u201d both figuratively and literally\nlets itg light shine before men.\nOn top of the church, situated at Sixteenth street and Columbia road north\nwest, is a sixteen-foot electric sign which shines every night in the year until 2\no'clock, often later.\nThe congregation has been worshiping under the lead of Rev. George ERE.\nWhitehouse in an oid dwelling house at the corner indicated. Plans, however, for\na new edifice to cost $100,000 have been drawn up and ground will shortly \u2018be\nbroken for its construction.\nThis church was organized March 29, 1906, with forty-four members. Percy 8.\nFoster, present superintendent of the Sunday school, was one of those who issued\nthe first call.\nAt present the mumber who attend services conducted by Rev. Whitehouse,\nwho came to Was on from Moncton, New Brunswick, is too large for the\ncapacity of the building.\nITS LIGHT LITERALLY SHINES.\nAnd Its Pastor. Rev. George E Whitehouse.\nImmanuel Baptist Church\nTHE WASEINGTON HERALD, SUNDAY, OCTOBER 13, 1907.\n\nwhen he retired, Mr. Botassi, the present\nconsular agent in New York, remained\nhere as charge. He was followed by\nM. Gennadius, mentiened above.\nAnother intended move on the part\nof the Greek government is the ap\npointment of a Greek bishop for the\nUnited States, who is to have sole ju\nrisdiction over the many communicants\nof the Greek faith residing in this\ncountry. The seat of the new bishop\nwill either be in this city or at New\nYork, and It is expected among the\nGreek colony here that hig name will\nbe announced in the course of a few\ndays. There ig small Greek church\nin this city, where the spiritual wel\nfare of the three hundred and odd\nGrecks is looked after by a regular\npriest of the Orthodox Greek Church.\n\n\n\nCOLORED TRAINING SCHOOL.\nHeadquarters Established for the\nNational Industrial Institute,\n\nTemporary headquarters of the cam\npaign committee of the National Training\nand Industrial Institute, to be established\nin the District of Columbia for colored\nboys and girls, has been opened at 1742\nFourteenth street northwest, with Mrs.\nAnna J. Cooper in charge.\nA very complete and interesting pam\nphlet has been issued, giving a full ac\ncount of the plans and scope of the work\nup to date. It contains the cuts of Gen.\nJohn B. Henderson, Commissioner H. -B.\nMacfarland, chairman of the advisory\ncommittee, and others. This pamphiet is\nto be used according to the promoter,\nRev. S. Geriah Lamkins, in the campaign\nwhich is now on for the raising of $60,000,\nwith which to begin the building opera\ntions.\n\n\n\n\nMaj. Charles R. Douglass, the son of\nthe late Frederick Douglass, is chairman\nof the campaign committee on the part\nof the men. Henry Lassiter is vice chair\nman. Mrs. Julia Mason Layton is chair\nman of the women's committee, Miss\nMattie R. Bowen, vice chairman, Mrs.\nAnna J. Coeper is field secretary. Dr.\nWilliam H. Davis, the executive secre\ntary of the campaign committee, is as\nsisted by Miss Cora J. Hawkins.\n\n\n\nArrangements have been completed for\nthe holding of a big mass meeting in the\ninterest of the school at 3 o'clock Sunday\nafternoon, October 20, 197, in the Metro\npolitan Baptist Churth, R street, between\nTwelfth and Thirteenth streets north\nwest, Dr. M. W. D. Norman, pastor.\n\nGen. John B. Henderson, ex-Senator\nfrom Missouri, who offered the first\namendment to the constitution abolishing\nslavery, and who subscribed the first\nmoney toward the establishment of the\nschool here, has accepted the invitation\nto preside.\n\nCHANLER ONOUTLOOK\nTakes an Optimistic View of\nBusiness Situation,\nNOT A CALAMITY CANDIDATE\nStock Gamblers, He Says, Know\nNothing About the Country's Fros\nperity and Have Nothing te De\nwith It\u2014Trade Conditions as Shown\nby Recent Statisties Are Good,\n\nNew York, Get. 12\u2014-It is a significant\nfact, and one worthy of attention at this\ntime, that of all the Democratic candi\ndates now mentioned for Presidential\nhonors the only one who seems to take\nan optimistic view of the business situa\ntion is Lieut. Gov. Lewis Stuyvesant\nChanler, of this State,\nWilliam Jennings Bryan, in the opinion\nof Democrats here, is doing his best to\nhold up the traditional argument that\nthe Democratic party can never succeed\nexcept upon a calamity issue. Other can\ndidates are viewing \u201cwith alarm\u201d what\nthey declare to be a serious disturbance\nin commercial life,\nThat Chanler has taken the converse of\nthis proposition shows that the young\nNew York Democrat has been doing a\nlittle thinking on his own account. Sev\neral up-State New York counties have\nalready, in convention, indorsed him for\nthe Democratic nomination for the Presi\ndency, and the New York State Demo\ncratic committee would have done the\nsame thing at its recent meeting here had\nnot Gov. Chanler been apprised of the\nfact that a minority in the committee was\nopposed to such action. Leader Charles\nF. Murphy of Tammany Hall demon\nstrated that he controlled the committee\nabsolutely by a vote of 30 to 18, two mem\nbers being absent. He agreed with Gov.\nChanler, however, that unjess the indorse\nment were unanimous it would not be\na wise thing to do politically.\n\n\n\n\n\nHis Optimism Justified,\n\nThat Gov. Chanler is wise in taking an\noptimistic view of trade conditions is\njustified by statistics gathered by one of\nthe most important business institutions\nin New York. They show that, for July,\noutside of New York City, there was an\nincrease in bank clearances amounting\nto an average of 8 per cent, a greater in\ncrease in August, and a still greater in\ncrease in September.\n\ni\n\n\nThe crop yield for the coming year is\nestimated at $7,000,000,000, and the amount\nof money now held by savings banks in\nthis country is $3,000,000,000.\nDuring the last six months the rail\nroads have borrowed on short-time notes\nsome two hundred and fifty miliions of\ndollars. A greater part of this money\ncame from Western banks, and was\nloaned at a rate that will yield a very\nsubstantial interest on the money. This\n$250,000,000 goes into betterments, and, of\ncourse, that means into generai circula\ntion.\n\n\n\nThese figures will give a bird's-eye view\nof general business conditions, and have\nnothing whatever to do with stock mar\nket or gambling features in trade affairs.\nWall Street No Barometer.\nWall street has long since ceased to\nbe an accurate barometer for judging\nprosperity in this country. The gentle\nmen who have been hurt by the recent\nslump in stocks no doubt feel that this\ncountry is going to the demnition bow\nwows, but these gentlemen, as Gov.\nChanler pointed out in a recent speech,\nhave as much to do with the prosperity\nof the country as the flea on a dog has to\ndo with its locomotion. a\nA further evidence of the truth of wha\nis stated above may be gathered from\nthe weekly reports made by men en.\ngaged in the wholesale trade here. Ir\nevery line of trade there exists a ver)\nhopeful feeling.\nOrders for new stock show an average\nincrease over the orders for the same\ntime last year. This would seem to in\ndicate that retailers throughout the\ncountry had held aloof from buying un\ntil they were satisfied that there would\nbe no falling off in their respective lines\nof business. As long as this conditior\ncontinues to exist no one need seriously\nworry over the business outlook.\nHis Question Inanswerable,\nThe professor of English in one of our\nWestern colleges was noted for being\nvery absent-minded. It was his custom\nto cail the roll each morning before the\nlecture. One morning, after calling a\nname to which there was no response, he\nlooked up, and, peering over his spec\ntacles, he asked sharply:\n\u201cWho is the absent boy in the vacant\nchair I see before me?\u201d\nA Bunch of Heroes.\nFrom the Chicago News,\nMr. Carnegie will please order another\n\u2018hunch of hero medals. Dr. Wiley has\nfound a group of young men who are will\ning to be experimented en to show the\ndeadly effects of soda water and other\nWf Arink\nProsperity in Terms of Pie,\nFrom the Louisville Courier-Journal\nThe American crops aggregate $7,000,\n000,000, or $80 worth for every inhabitant.\nIn other words, your share is 1,600 aureate\npumpkin pies, And yet the calamity howl\ner howls!\nRESUMES SESSIONS\nUnited States Supreme Court\nOpens To-morrow.\nEND OF FOUR MONTHS\u2019 RECESS\nMany Important Cases on the Calen\ndar, Among Them the North Caro\nline Railroad and Standard Oil\nAppeals\u2014Judges\u2019 Customary Visit\nto the White House to Be Omitted,\nWith the simplest of ceremonies, the\nthird branch of the trinity that con\nstitutes: the government of the United\nStates of America\u2014the Supreme Court\n\u2014will resume its sessions to-morrow.\nIn fact, the opening is without cere\nmony and does not differ from the\nopening of the court every day that it\nis in session in its chamber in the Cap\n{tol 4\nThe court has been in recess for\nnearly four months, and to-morrow, a\nmoment or two before 12 noon, the\nmain corridor of the Capitol building,\nleading from the Senate to the House,\nwill be roped off with red silken cords\nhy the two ancient colored messengers\nof the court. When this is done, the\ndoor of the robing room on the west\nside of the building will be pushed\nopen and, headed by white-haired and\nvenerable Chief Justice Fuller, the\nseven associate justices, Harlan, Brew\ner, White, Peckhain, McKenna, Holmes,\nand Day, which i\u00a2 the order of their\nappointment to the court, will walk\ninto the courtroom and take their\nseats. They will be preceded by Mar\nshal J. M. Wright. All will be attired\nin black gowns, and when they are\nseated, the Chief Justice will nod to\nthe marshal, who will direet Crier\nGreen te make the usual announce\nment:\n\u201cOyez! Oyez! Ail persons having busi\nness before the Supreme Court of the\nUnited States are admonished to draw\nnear and give their attention, for the\ncourt is now sitting. God save the United\nStates and this honorable court.\u201d\n\ni\n\nAnd this is the manner in which what\nis updoubtedly the greatest judicial tri\n\u2018bunal in the world begins its delibgra\ntiens. As one of the three great coordi\n\u2018nate branches that form the government\nunder which we live, it has the last say\na8 to the validity of laws passed by\nCongress, and thus stands between the\npeople and the encroachments, if at.\ntempted, of its representatives in the two\nchambers that make up the legislative\nbranch.\n\n\n\nWill Not Visit White House.\nFrom time immemorial, after court has\nbeen formally opened it has been the\ncustom of the court to repair in carriages\nto the White House and present their re\nspects to the Chief Magistrate, This will\nbe omitted to-morrow, for if followed it\nwould be necessary for the aged justices\nto take a considerable journey te the\ncanebrakes in Louisiana and greet the\nPresident in the tent, which is now\ntemporarily serving as a White House,\n\n\n\nWhile decisions in some cases may be\nbanded down to-morrow, it is more likely\nthat the court, following its usual cus\ntom, will hold a brief session lasting\nabout an hour. The docket will in all\nprobability not be calied, and the busi\nness confined to hearing motions and ad\nmitting attorneys to practice before the\naugust body.\n\n\n\nMany Important Cases,\nThere wiil be many important matters\ncome before the court at this term for\nargument and for decision. The raliroad\nrate bill, designated by Senator Foraker,\nof Ohio, as unconstitutional, may reach\ne judicial attention of the court at this\nterm, and the first of the raliroad-rate\ncases from North Carolina, which threat\nened to involve the State and the United\nState judicial authorities in a serious\nconflict, has just been docketed. This\ncage comes from Buncombe County,\nN.C\n\n\ni\nI\n\n\nCommissioner J, F. Maher, who was\nappointed by the court to take testimony\nin connection with the contempt proceed\nings brought against Sheriff Shipp, eight\nof his deputies, and sixteen citizens of\nChattanooga, has completed the same\nand will file it with the court. The sheriff\nand the others mentioned were cited to\nappear before the Supreme Court last\nspring, to show cause why they should\nnot be punished for contempt of court,\nthe sheriff for dereliction of duty and\nthe sixteen citizens for aiding in the\nlynching of Ed Johnson, a negro. John\nson, who had been convicted of a crimi\nnal assault, secured, through his attor\nney, a writ of error from the Supreme\nCourt. The clerk of the court notified\nSheriff Shipp of this writ, which had the\neffect of staying the negro's execution.\nDespite the delay granted by the court, a\nmob stormed the jail In which Johnson\nwas confined, and lynched him. The\nsheriff and his deputies are charged with\nfailing to exercise diligence in protecting\nhim. The case has already been argued\nbefore the court on demurrer.\n\ni\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\n\n\nBefore the court adjourns former Rep\nresentative John N. Willlamson, of Ore\ngon, who was convicted in that State for\ni\nalleged land frauds, and wi, 4 appealed,\nwill know whether or not he will have to\nspend a few months in jail.\n\ni\n\n\nThe case of the New York Central Rail\nroad, which was fined $118,00\u00a2 for allowing\nthe American Sugar Refining Company\nalleged illegal rebates by the United\nUnited States Court for the Southern dis\ntrict of New York, and which was ap\npealed to the Supreme Court, will also be\ntaken up.\nt\n\nAnother interesting case which the\ncourt will be called upon to decide is\nthat brought forward by the Louisville\nand Nashville Railroad. The railroad in\nthis case attacks the legality of the anti\npass provision of the railroad-rate aet.\n\n\nCassie Chadwick's Jewelry,\nIt is expected that at an early date a\nmotion will be made involving jewelry\nh\u00a5roiaetated by Mrs. Cassie Chadwick,\nwho a few days ago in the peniten\ntiary at Columbus, Ohio. Collector Leach,\nof Cleveland, and Adrian H. Larkin, a\nNew York lawyer, are fighting for the\nnosgsaesion of this jewelry The jewels in\nIt is expected that at an early date a\nmotion will be made involving jewelry\nhypothecated by Mrs. Cassie Chadwick,\nwho di a few days ago in the peniten\ntiary at Columbus, Ohio. Collector Leach,\nof Cleveland, and Adrian H. Larkin, a\nNew York lawyer, are fighting for the\npossession of this jewelry. The jewels in\nquestion are alleged to have been smug.\ngled into this country by Mrs. Chadwick\nto avoid the payment of duty. While\nthey were in Larkin's possession Leach\nborrowed them to have them examined.\nLeach shipped then: to Cleveiand, refus\ning to return them to Larkin, into whose\nhands they had come after being used by\nMrs. Chadwick to secure a loan. Ag the\ndecision of the lower court has been\nagainst the collector, it is not believed\nthe government will vigorously fight the\n\u2018motion to dismiss the suit.\n~The Savings Deposit Bank and Trust\nCompany, of Elyria, Ohio, will also bring\n\u2018another new case before the court, which\n\u2018was caused by Mrs. Chadwick's activity\nin the money market. The claim of the\n\u2018bank is for a preference to chattels, in.\ncluding household furniture, bric-a-brac,\npictures, &ec., of her former Euclid ave\nn residence in Cleveland, on the\npv Ay of a mortgage given just be\nfore the disclosures which resulted in\nTAR\n74\nel\nERMANENT,\nshaperetain\ning sack suits.\nNot pressed to look\nright on sight, but London\nshrunk and hand-tailored to\nkeep on looking right all the\ntime.\nKirschbaum clothes are\ndistinguished by a style and\n\u201cnaturalness\u201d that mark them\nin any company.\nLook for the Kirschbaum\nlabel. Prices, $15 to $30.\nA. B. Kirschbaum Co,\n(Makers)\nPhiladelphia and New York.\nCassie's undoing. The decision of the\nlover court is against giving the bank\nany preference.\n\nLegality of High Tax.\nThe city of Chicago will ask to have\nconsidered by the court at an early date\nits suit involving the legality of a high\ntax on public utilities of that city; and\nthe right of Georgia to collect taxes as\nsessed upon the Central of Georgia Rail\nroad Company and the Georgia Rail\nroad for stock of the Western Railway\nof Alabama wiil be taken up early in the\nterm.\nThe case in which a $20,000,000 fine was\nassessed by Judge Landis against the\nStandard Gi! Company will also be ar\ngued before the court at this term.\nThere are already 460 suits docketed,\nabout fifty more than at the correspond\ning date of last year, the largest numbet\nof new cases ever recorded at one term.\n\n\nEANNS ANNOUNCE SILK SALE.\n\nQuote Ynasual Values in Silks and\nWoolen Dress Goods,\n\n\nTo-morrow will witness a rustle in silks\n\u2018at 8. Kann, Sons Co., if the silk sale\nadvertised by this firm to-day is appre\nciat\u00e9d as it should be, judging by the\nunusual values quoted, and the astonish\ningly low price at which these silks are\noffered. Two hundred full pieces of nov\nelty silks will go at a saving averaging\na little less than half.\n\n\n\n\nWool dress goods in splendidly com\nplete displays will also be an attraction,\nand doubtless call forth many expressions\nof satisfaction from discriminating wo\nmen who may have a chance to revel in\nextensive assortments from which they\nmay select the material for the winter\ncostume,\nThe woman who is in a hurry for her\nsuit, and doesn\u2019t want to wait to have\none made, may be well satisfied if she\nselects from those advertised by this\nfirm to-morrow, and feel that she is in\ndeed saving money; the only proviso is\nthat she be of the proper size, as the lot\nconsists of broken sizes and ends of lines\nthat have caused most unprecedented\nsales during the past two or three weeks.\nSo much for the outer aderning of wo\nmenkind, street wear, &c. The next turn\nshould be to investigate the offering of\nkimonas and negligees, those comfortable\nlittle house garments that, having once\nformed the habit of wearing, no woman\nwill want to be without.\n\n\n\nA big sale of silver purses will have\nits attraction for those who keep up to\nthe latest in all those little accesories\nand fads of the moment, of which this is\nthe latest. g\nThose who propose large entertaining\nthis season will read with interest\nthe offerings in linens, and be delighted\nto know at what savings they will be\nable to buy to-morrow. The necessities\nof life, such as blankets and comforts,\nwill appeal to the careful housewife whe\nlooks to the comfort of her household.\n\nAbdul Hamid as a Humorist.\nPopular conception of Abdul Hamid,\nSultan of Turkey, does not accredit him\nwith a sense of humor, says the Pitts\nburg Dispatch, yet we are assured on\nhigh authority that the Sultan not only\nenjoys a joke, but is capable of perpetrat\ning one,\n\n\n\nOn one occasion the grand vizier gave\nan elaborate dinner, following which a\ndervish magician gave an exhibition. In\ndescribing the magician's feals to the\nSultan the next day, one of the court of\nficials exclaimed:\n\n\u201cWould vou believe it, sire, that poor\nderviesh swallowed silver soons one after\nthe other. It was simply marvelous.\u201d\n\u201cMarvelous?\u201d inquired the Sultan, \u201cI\ndo not see anything so marvelous in the\nfact that a r dervish swallowed a few\nof the grand vizier's silver spoons. Has\nsan Pasha, my minister of the navy, used\nto swallow entire ironclads without even\ngo much as changing the color of his\n$c, st Fusseil's aug-u\nfara\nPark Memorial to Gov, Hoge.\nFrom the Austin Statesman.\nThe Hogg Memorial Park Lake Asso\nclatiof, having been chartered, organized\nand officered, Is now ready for business.\nThe plan is to make, in perpetuation of\nthe late Gov. Hogg, the most attractive,\nbeautiful, and extensive park and pleas\nure lake in all the country.\nWe quote WHOLESALE Prices at Retail,\nPICTURE FRAMES TO ORDER.\nREGILDINCG OF OLD FRAMES A SPECIALTY.\nGlad to Submit Estimates at Any Time.\n\u201cWe Particularly Solicit Particular Work.\u201d\nJ. W. NIEPOLD SON\n810 E Street N. W.\nNORFOLK WASHINGTON\nSTEAMBOAT CO,\nJ amestown\nExposition,\nPotomac River,\nChesapeake Bay,\nHampton Roads,\nBY NIGHT AND DAY.\nSteamers Daily,\n8a. m.\u2014\u20146:30 p.m.\nIncluding Sundays.\nLand passengers at Exposi\ntion Grounds.\nModern Steel Steamers.\nHandsomely equipped.\nTickets and information st City Ticket\nOffice, Colorado Bldg, 14th apd C ow. or\nat Wharf, foot of Tth st. sw.\nNORFOLK WASHINGTON\nSTEAMBOAT CO.\nFORTY MILES\nDOWN THE POTOMAC\nPassing Indian Head and Quantico.\nSTEAMER CHARLES MACALESTER\nSunday, October 13, 1907,\nLEAVES AT 2:3 P. M.\nHOME AT 730 P. M.\nSTOPS MADE AT ALEXANDRIA.\nFare, Round Trip, 25\u00a2.\nNEW DAY LINE TO\nJamestown and Norfolk\nAT REDUCED RATES,\nFARE, $25, ROUND TRIP; $.350, one way;\n$4.00 to Richmond and return.\nLeave Washington, Riley's Wharf, 6th st. sw., at\n8 a. m. Tuesdays, Thursdays, and Saturdays. Re\nturning, leave 